          "body": "Immediately after the announcement, Yahweh removes Elijah from the scene: 'Go away from here and turn eastward, and hide yourself' (17:3). The command is counter-intuitive. A prophet who has just delivered a national judgment might expect to remain in place, to pastor the crisis. Instead, he is sent to a wadi east of the Jordan with a supply chain that would have scandalized any Israelite: ravens. Ravens are listed among the unclean birds in Leviticus 11:15 and Deuteronomy 14:14 — birds that scavenged carrion, that no pious Jew would eat. Yet Yahweh 'commanded' them (tsavah, the word used for sovereign royal orders) to bring Elijah bread and meat twice daily. The choice is theologically pointed: God will sustain His prophet through the most ritually improbable agents rather than through conventional religious channels. The obedience note in 17:5 — 'he went and did according to the word of the LORD' — will be the template against which the widow's obedience in 17:15 is measured. The brook's eventual drying (17:7) is not failure of the provision but transition to the next assignment. The prophet must live with the drought he announced until the God who sent him to the wilderness sends him elsewhere."
