          "body": "The chapter ends with a two-clause confession from the Phoenician widow: 'Now I know that you are a man of God, and that the word of the LORD in your mouth is truth' (17:24). The word emet — truth, reliability, verified fact — is the Hebrew term for something proven trustworthy through experience. The widow does not confess a doctrine; she confesses a history. She has watched flour not exhaust and oil not empty day after day. She has received her dead son back alive. The cumulative evidence has been sufficient: Yahweh's word, mediated through His prophet, has proven itself reliable at every point where it could have failed. This confession is the theological destination the entire chapter has been building toward. Three miracles, escalating in intensity from the unusual to the impossible, converge on this single sentence from a Gentile woman in Sidon. The narrator's argument is complete: the God who announced drought is the God who provides in drought, the God who controls fertility in Baal's own country, and the God who raises the dead. The word of the LORD in His prophet's mouth is truth."
